One member of the Labour Party said his group is concerned that it “rhymes with Twp and Pwp.”
For readers outside Wales: in Welsh twp means stupid and pwp means poop.
A member of the Plaid party said the group as a whole was "not happy" and suggested alternatives.
The Welsh Conservative said his group approaches the name change "with an open mind", but noted that the MWP is close to the word Muppet.
In this context, the Welsh letter "w" is pronounced similarly to the letter "u" in Yorkshire English.
The Assembly Commission, which is now preparing legislation to introduce name changes, said: "The final decision on how members of the Welsh Assembly will be called will, of course, be up to the members themselves."
The Welsh Government Act of 2017 gave the Welsh Assembly the power to change its name.
In June, the commission published the results of a public consultation on the proposals, where wide support was received by the variant of calling the assembly the Welsh Parliament.
As for the title of Assembly members, the committee preferred the name Welsh Parliament Member, or WMP, but the MWP variant received the most support in the public debate.
Members of the Assembly are apparently proposing alternative options, but the struggle to reach a consensus may bring concerns to President Elin Jones, who is due to table a draft legislation within weeks.
Reform laws will include further changes to the functioning of the assembly, including rules on disqualification of members and a draft committee system.
