Sainsbury's plans to enter the UK cosmetics market
Sainsbury’s wants to take on Boots, Superdrug and Debenhams with store-style beauty aisles, where specialist saleswomen will be available.
With the UK cosmetics market taking a strong take-up of 2.8 billion pounds and continuing to grow as fashion and household goods sales decline, cosmetics aisles will be tested in 11 stores across the country and, if successful, spread to other stores next year.
The investment in cosmetics is linked to supermarkets’ efforts to find uses for shelves previously used for televisions, microwave ovens and household items.
Sainsbury’s says it will double its beauty product offering to 3,000 products, including brands such as Revlon, Essie, Tweezerman and Dr. PawPaw.
The existing range from L'Oreal, Maybelline and Burt's Bees will also get more space thanks to branded locations similar to those in stores like Boots.
The supermarket also reintroduces its range of Boutique makeup, so most products will be vegan, which young customers are increasingly demanding.
In addition, two Saintsbury’s stores will test the franchises of Fragrance Shop, the first such store opened last week in Croydon, south London, and the next this year in Selly Oak, Birmingham.
Online shopping and the shift to shopping for small amounts of food in local stores means supermarkets need to do more to attract people.
Sainsbury's CEO Mike Coupe says stores will increasingly look like department stores as the supermarket chain tries to better offer services and non-food products to fight discount retailers such as Aldi and Lidl.
Sainsbury's has opened hundreds of Argos stores and has also introduced a number of Habitat departments, which are the chains it bought two years ago. This has increased food sales and makes acquisitions even more profitable.
The previous attempt of the supermarket to remake the department with a cosmetic and pharmacy assortment ended infamously.
At the beginning of the millennium, Sainsbury’s tested a joint venture with Boots, but the connection ended after a dispute over the distribution of drug revenues in supermarkets.
The new strategy comes three years after Saintsbury’s sold its 281 pharmacies for 125 million pounds to the firm of Celesio, which owns the Lloyds pharmacy chain.
Lloyds is set to play its part by adding an expanded range of luxury skincare brands including La Roche-Posay and Vichy to its four stores.
Paul Mills-Hicks, Sales Director at Sainsbury’s, said: “We have changed the look and feel of our cosmetics aisles to improve the environment for our customers.
We have also invested in specially trained colleagues that customers will be able to consult.
Our range of brands should satisfy all needs and the enticing environment and convenient location mean we are now an attractive place to buy cosmetics that are changing the old ways of shopping."
