‘The sea is ours’: Inland Bolivia hopes court reopens way to Pacific Ocean
Sailors patrol outside the naval headquarters in La Paz, which is decorated with ropes.
Above the public buildings is a blue flag in the color of the ocean.
Sea bases off Lake Titicaca for the Amazon are described by the slogan: “The sea is rightfully ours.
It is our duty to get it.”
Throughout landlocked Bolivia, there is still a vivid memory of the coasts that the country lost in favor of Chile in the bloody resource war of the 19th century - as well as the desire to roam the Pacific Ocean again.
These aspirations are perhaps the greatest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the international court, which is expected to fall on October 1 after five years of negotiations.
“Bolivia has energy, a spirit of unity and calm, and of course expects a positive outcome,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will follow the MSD's decision on big screens across the country with the hope that the tribunal in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia's claim that - after many decades of intermittent talks - Chile is obliged to negotiate granting Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president Evo Morales - who faces a controversial re-election battle next year - is also very interested in Monday's decision.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia - and even if it did, much would have changed.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no power to assign Chilean territory to anyone and said it would not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the MSD decision comes just six months after the last arguments were made shows that the case “wasn’t complicated,” as Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law, says.
And the last four years have not only failed to support the cause of Bolivia, but may have hindered it.
“The current Bolivian government has taken over the issues of access to the sea,” Zarate says.
He adds that Morales' offensive rhetoric has weakened all of Chile's remaining goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will one day start negotiating again, but after that it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually quick.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an exceptional opportunity to usher in a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also refused that Morales - still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - would use the question of the sea as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“A judgment is an opportunity to find out that we need to deal with the past.”
