John Edward: Language skills are a must for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have had a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other outstanding exam results. Individual and group achievements in sports, arts, music and other community activities underline this.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools are represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and strive to provide their pupils and parents with the best possible level of service.
Independent schools prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the careers they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement individually tailored school education plans, we observe that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart."
This is an important observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s exams show that languages are at the top of the charts, with independent schools having the highest success rates.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved the highest A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland promote foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by pupils are equally valued in the study plans of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, technical fields and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that, for reasons cited by employers as problems in filling vacancies, 17 per cent are language skills deficient.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalized world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, namely 15 percent, being French.
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially the languages of emerging economies, they will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
A number of schools focus on more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in the outlook to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, they will always have a choice of several languages at independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages are vitally important to the country's future in the global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools
