North Korea says it will not disarm unilaterally and without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister said on Saturday that continued U.N. sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and in such circumstances the country would never give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told his annual general assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site of nuclear tests, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see an adequate response from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and in such circumstances it is impossible to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri echoed known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for every gradual step, his statement appeared significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization just because Pyongyang had already gone through it in the past.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work to “denuclearize the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees of North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 war, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure on sanctions to enforce its goals, even objecting to ‘declaring an end to the war’,” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our mistrust."
Ri made no mention of the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the American leader stressed at the UN earlier in the week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If South Korea and not the US were to side with this issue of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not come into such a stalemate."
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s targeting of U.S. missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump described Kim as a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much work still needs to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is completely denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it, saying, "If it takes two years, three years, or five months -- it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and ceaselessly until we become aware of complete, final, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously supported sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to suppress Pyongyang's funding of nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo and Ri met at the UN General Assembly party, and Pompeo said he would visit Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not end well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that progress had been made only for North Korea to declare within hours that it was making “gangster demands.”
North Korea has pledged to meet with Moon this month to dismantle the missile site and also the nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” he hoped for were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take part in a course to teach them enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has made all of its students sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying all night long while students are awake and cheering themselves up with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most renowned university are often clueless when it comes to the basics of self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women's Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to begin the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were really seriously sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive assignments.
In one section, there is a picture of student dormitories where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleeping habits.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
However, we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of cigarette smoking," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “studying all night” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also on the rise.
Getting enough good quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, making the person still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes took during his freshman year at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the entire course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor advised students to consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can upset your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
