This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating meadows, and best practices in maintaining forested areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined greatly in the past century.
They are threatened as a result of construction and territorial development affecting the colonies and the natural environment.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as fly traps and chemical treatments for building materials, as well as cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
Because they hunt at night, however, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to track bugs and obstacles in flight.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
